    "caption": "The jungle bird with a beak longer than its whole body would suggest.",
    "shortDescription": "A toucan's oversized bill looks heavy, but it's actually hollow — a lightweight structure of bone struts filled with air, weighing almost nothing. It's also a great radiator: blood flows through a network of vessels in the beak, releasing body heat to cool the toucan down, like opening a window. Toucans use that beak to pluck fruit from branches just out of reach. Fun fact: A toucan's beak has serrated edges — like a tiny bread knife — which helps it grip slippery fruit."
